  title="How Much Gravel Do I Need? [Calculator + Charts] | Yard Metric"
  description="How to calculate gravel for any project. Driveway, walkway, and patio examples with exact cubic yard and ton quantities, plus a depth chart and ordering checklist."
  canonical="https://yardmetric.com/guides/how-much-gravel-do-i-need/"
>
  <Fragment slot="structured-data">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={structuredData} />
  </Fragment>

  <NavBar />

  <main>
    <div class="container">

      <div class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span>/</span>
        <a href="/guides/">Guides</a>
        <span>/</span>
        <span>How Much Gravel Do I Need?</span>
      </div>

      <article class="guide">

        <header class="guide-header">
          <span class="guide-tag">Landscaping Guide</span>
          <h1>How Much Gravel Do I Need?</h1>
          <p class="guide-intro">A standard 12×50 ft driveway at 4 inches deep needs <strong>7.4 cubic yards of gravel - about 10.4 tons</strong>. That is the answer most people are looking for. This guide shows you how to calculate that number for any driveway, walkway, patio, or drainage bed, and what to tell your supplier when you call to order.</p>
          <a href="/calculators/gravel-calculator/" class="cta-button">Use the Gravel Calculator →</a>
        </header>

        <section class="section">
          <h2>The Formula (and Why ÷ 324)</h2>
          <p>Every gravel quantity comes down to this:</p>
          <div class="formula-block">
            <pre>Cubic Yards = Length (ft) × Width (ft) × Depth (in) ÷ 324</pre>
          </div>
          <p>The number 324 is not arbitrary. One cubic yard equals 27 cubic feet, and one foot equals 12 inches. So: 27 × 12 = 324. When you multiply square feet by depth in inches, dividing by 324 converts the result to cubic yards in a single step.</p>
          <p>To get tons, multiply cubic yards by the density of your gravel type. Standard crushed gravel (#57 stone, 3/4") weighs <strong>1.4 tons per cubic yard</strong>. Pea gravel is slightly lighter at <strong>1.3 tons per cubic yard</strong>.</p>
          <div class="formula-block">
            <pre>Tons = Cubic Yards × 1.4  (crushed gravel)
Tons = Cubic Yards × 1.3  (pea gravel)</pre>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
          <h2>Driveway Examples</h2>
          <p>These are the most common driveway sizes at the standard 4-inch depth for passenger vehicles. Add 15% to each for compaction loss and ordering buffer.</p>
          <div class="table-wrapper">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Driveway Size</th>
                  <th>Depth</th>
                  <th>Cubic Yards</th>
                  <th>Tons (×1.4)</th>
                  <th>+15% Order Qty</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>10 × 20 ft</td><td>4"</td><td>2.47</td><td>3.5</td><td>2.84 yd³ / 4.0 tons</td></tr>
                <tr><td>12 × 50 ft</td><td>4"</td><td>7.41</td><td>10.4</td><td>8.5 yd³ / 12.0 tons</td></tr>
                <tr><td>14 × 80 ft</td><td>4"</td><td>13.83</td><td>19.4</td><td>15.9 yd³ / 22.3 tons</td></tr>
                <tr><td>16 × 100 ft</td><td>4"</td><td>19.75</td><td>27.7</td><td>22.7 yd³ / 31.8 tons</td></tr>
                <tr><td>12 × 50 ft</td><td>6"</td><td>11.11</td><td>15.6</td><td>12.8 yd³ / 17.9 tons</td></tr>
                <tr><td>14 × 80 ft</td><td>6"</td><td>20.74</td><td>29.0</td><td>23.9 yd³ / 33.4 tons</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p>Use 6 inches for driveways that will carry trucks, RVs, or vehicles heavier than 10,000 lbs. Use 4 inches for standard passenger vehicles on a prepared sub-base. If you are skipping the road base layer, add 2 inches to these depth figures.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
          <h2>Walkway Examples</h2>
          <p>Walkways and garden paths use 2–3 inches of gravel. Two inches is sufficient for foot traffic on a stable sub-base; 3 inches provides better weed suppression and a more stable surface underfoot.</p>
          <div class="table-wrapper">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Path Size</th>
                  <th>Depth</th>
                  <th>Cubic Yards</th>
                  <th>Tons (×1.4)</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>3 × 20 ft</td><td>2"</td><td>0.37</td><td>0.52</td></tr>
                <tr><td>3 × 50 ft</td><td>2"</td><td>0.93</td><td>1.30</td></tr>
                <tr><td>4 × 100 ft</td><td>2"</td><td>2.47</td><td>3.46</td></tr>
                <tr><td>3 × 20 ft</td><td>3"</td><td>0.56</td><td>0.78</td></tr>
                <tr><td>3 × 50 ft</td><td>3"</td><td>1.39</td><td>1.94</td></tr>
                <tr><td>4 × 100 ft</td><td>3"</td><td>3.70</td><td>5.18</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
          <h2>Patio and Outdoor Area Examples</h2>
          <p>Gravel patios and outdoor living areas typically use 3–4 inches for a clean decorative finish. Angular pea-size crushed stone or pea gravel are common choices here. Use these figures as your starting quantity - add 10% before ordering.</p>
          <div class="table-wrapper">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Area Size</th>
                  <th>Depth</th>
                  <th>Cubic Yards</th>
                  <th>Tons (×1.4)</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>12 × 12 ft</td><td>3"</td><td>1.33</td><td>1.87</td></tr>
                <tr><td>16 × 16 ft</td><td>3"</td><td>2.37</td><td>3.32</td></tr>
                <tr><td>20 × 20 ft</td><td>3"</td><td>3.70</td><td>5.19</td></tr>
                <tr><td>20 × 20 ft</td><td>4"</td><td>4.94</td><td>6.92</td></tr>
                <tr><td>30 × 30 ft</td><td>3"</td><td>8.33</td><td>11.67</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
          <h2>Parking Area Examples</h2>
          <p>Unpaved parking areas need 4–6 inches of compacted gravel on a stable base. Light-use areas (a few vehicles occasionally): 4 inches. Regular daily use: 5–6 inches. Any area that handles trucks: 6 inches minimum with a road base layer beneath.</p>
          <div class="table-wrapper">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Parking Area</th>
                  <th>Depth</th>
                  <th>Cubic Yards</th>
                  <th>Tons (×1.4)</th>
                  <th>+15% Order Qty</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>2 spaces (18×20 ft)</td><td>4"</td><td>4.44</td><td>6.2</td><td>5.1 yd³ / 7.2 tons</td></tr>
                <tr><td>4 spaces (20×40 ft)</td><td>4"</td><td>9.88</td><td>13.8</td><td>11.4 yd³ / 15.9 tons</td></tr>
                <tr><td>10 spaces (30×60 ft)</td><td>6"</td><td>33.3</td><td>46.7</td><td>38.3 yd³ / 53.6 tons</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </section>

        <div class="cta-inline">
          <p>Get your exact quantity in seconds - no math required.</p>
          <a href="/calculators/gravel-calculator/" class="cta-button">Open the Gravel Calculator →</a>
        </div>

        <section class="section">
          <h2>Gravel Depth Chart by Use Case</h2>
          <p>The depth you choose determines how much gravel you need - and whether the installation will actually work. Under-depth gravel ruts, shifts, and fails. This chart shows the correct depth for each use case.</p>
          <div class="table-wrapper">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Use Case</th>
                  <th>Recommended Depth</th>
                  <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>Decorative ground cover</td><td>2 inches</td><td>Under decks, no vehicle traffic</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Garden walkway / path</td><td>2–3 inches</td><td>Foot traffic only; 3" for better weed suppression</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Driveway (passenger cars)</td><td>4 inches compacted</td><td>Over compacted road base sub-base</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Driveway (trucks / RV)</td><td>6 inches compacted</td><td>Over 4" compacted road base</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Parking area (light use)</td><td>4 inches</td><td>Stable native soil sub-base required</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Parking area (heavy use)</td><td>6 inches</td><td>Road base layer strongly recommended</td></tr>
                <tr><td>French drain / trench</td><td>Full trench depth</td><td>12" typical; use clean open-graded #57 stone</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Drainage bed</td><td>6–12 inches</td><td>Deeper for higher water flow volumes</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Patio gravel surface</td><td>3–4 inches</td><td>Angular stone or pea gravel over landscape fabric</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
          <h2>Gravel Types Quick Reference</h2>
          <p>Not all gravel is the same. The type you choose affects compaction, drainage, stability, and cost. This table covers the most common options for residential projects.</p>
          <div class="table-wrapper">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Type</th>
                  <th>Size</th>
                  <th>Compacts?</th>
                  <th>Best For</th>
                  <th>Avoid For</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>#57 Crushed Stone</td><td>3/4"</td><td>Yes</td><td>Driveways, parking, base layers</td><td>Decorative paths</td></tr>
                <tr><td>#21A / Dense Grade</td><td>3/4" minus (w/ fines)</td><td>Excellent</td><td>Tight compacted surfaces, road base</td><td>Drainage (fines block flow)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Pea Gravel</td><td>1/4"–3/8"</td><td>No</td><td>Drainage, playgrounds, decorative</td><td>Driveways (shifts constantly)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Crusher Run</td><td>Mixed 3/4" to dust</td><td>Excellent</td><td>Sub-base under asphalt, concrete</td><td>Surface layer (too rough)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>River Rock</td><td>3/4"–3"</td><td>No</td><td>Dry creek beds, water features</td><td>Driveways, structural bases</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Road Base</td><td>Mixed 1.5" to dust</td><td>Excellent</td><td>Driveway base layer, structural fill</td><td>Drainage (fines restrict flow)</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
          <h2>Cubic Yards vs Tons - What Your Supplier Actually Uses</h2>
          <p>This is where most homeowners get confused. Your calculator gives you both numbers - here is when each one matters.</p>
          <p><strong>Order by the cubic yard when:</strong> you are comparing prices between suppliers, the project is small (under 2 tons), or you are filling a specific volume (a raised bed, a trench, a specific depth in a defined area). Cubic yards are a volume measurement - they tell you exactly how much space you are filling.</p>
          <p><strong>Order by the ton when:</strong> the supplier's minimum is quoted in tons, you are scheduling a delivery where the truck weight affects route permits, or you are comparing against a previous project billed by weight. Most quarries and bulk suppliers price by the ton for large orders.</p>
          <p>The conversion is straightforward: <strong>1 cubic yard of standard crushed gravel = 1.4 tons</strong>. If your supplier quotes $45 per ton and you need 7.4 cubic yards, you need 10.4 tons at a cost of approximately $468 in material (before delivery).</p>
          <p><strong>Watch out for wet-weight pricing.</strong> Bulk gravel sits in outdoor storage and is often weighed wet. Wet gravel can weigh up to 10% more than dry gravel per cubic yard. If a supplier gives you a ton price and the material is weighed wet, you may receive slightly less volume than expected. For large orders, ask whether the price is wet or dry weight.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
          <h2>Before You Order - 8-Point Checklist</h2>
          <ol class="checklist">
            <li><strong>Measure after grading, not before.</strong> Ground irregularities and excavation can change your calculated area. Measure the actual finished footprint.</li>
            <li><strong>Choose your depth based on use case, not cost.</strong> Under-depth gravel fails within one season. Use the depth chart above.</li>
            <li><strong>Add 10–15% to your calculated quantity.</strong> 10% for flat decorative areas, 15% for driveways and sloped sites where compaction loss is higher.</li>
            <li><strong>Confirm the unit with your supplier.</strong> Cubic yard or ton? Write it down. Ordering the wrong unit doubles your cost or leaves you 30% short.</li>
            <li><strong>Ask about wet vs dry weight.</strong> If they weigh wet, you are receiving less volume per ton than the dry calculation implies.</li>
            <li><strong>Order base layer and surface gravel separately.</strong> Road base and #57 stone are different products. Get a line item for each if your driveway uses a two-layer system.</li>
            <li><strong>Check minimum delivery.</strong> Most bulk suppliers have a 1 cubic yard (about 1.4 tons) minimum. Plan small projects to meet this threshold or add bags to fill the gap.</li>
            <li><strong>Ask about lead time for specialty sizes.</strong> Standard #57 stone is almost always in stock. Specialty sizes, recycled concrete aggregate, and decorative colored stone may need 3–7 days.</li>
          </ol>
        </section>

        <div class="cta-final">
          <h3>Ready to Calculate Your Gravel?</h3>
          <p>Enter your dimensions in the Yard Metric gravel calculator and get cubic yards, tons, and bag count instantly - with the compaction factor already built in.</p>
          <a href="/calculators/gravel-calculator/" class="cta-button">Calculate Your Gravel →</a>
        </div>

      </article>
    </div>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>

